# Majority Element II

## Problem

Given an array of size **n**, find all elements that appear **more than ⌊ n/3 ⌋ times**.

Return all such elements.

---

### Example

```
Input:
arr = [3,2,3]

Output:
[3]
```

Example 2:

```
Input:
arr = [1,1,1,3,3,2,2,2]

Output:
[1,2]
```

---

# Important Observation

For **n/3**, there can be **at most 2 majority elements**.

Why?

```
More than n/3
Only 2 numbers can satisfy this
```

---

# 1. Brute Force

Count frequency for each element.

Time → **O(n²)**

(Not used in interviews)

---

# 2. Better Approach (HashMap)

### C++ Code

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

vector<int> majorityElement(vector<int>& arr)
{
    int n = arr.size();
    unordered_map<int,int> mp;

    for(int x : arr)
        mp[x]++;

    vector<int> ans;

    for(auto it : mp)
    {
        if(it.second > n/3)
            ans.push_back(it.first);
    }

    return ans;
}

int main()
{
    vector<int> arr = {1,1,1,3,3,2,2,2};

    vector<int> ans = majorityElement(arr);

    for(int x : ans)
        cout << x << " ";
}
```

Time → **O(n)**
Space → **O(n)**

